I'm actually using a similar method to sprout black locust trees. However instead of stratifying (yes that's the correct word for the process) in a fridge, I use a different approach. Black locust seeds don't respond too well to cold stratification, so instead I use scarification (yes, that's also a real word and appropriate for the process I use). Basically I put the seeds in a tea strainer, and quickly pour over the seeds and through the strainer a cup of boiling water. Sounds extreme, but it works. The seeds are only in contact with the boiling water for a second or two, then it flows away through the holes in the strainer. The seeds get a thermal shock which awakes them and makes them sprout. I then put them in a moist folded paper towel in a bag and leave them on the counter for a couple weeks. It's actually best to not completely close the bag as the seeds need air to sprout. Then I plant them directly outside. Many sprouted seeds will die when you plant them outside instead of in a pot first, but those that survive will grow strong trees.
